$$
x^{2}-x y+y^{2} \geq x y \text { and } x^{6}-x^{3} y^{3}+y^{6} \geq x^{3} y^{3}
$$

Therefore,

$$
\begin{aligned}
x^{9}+y^{9} & =(x+y)\left(x^{2}-x y+y^{2}\right)\left(x^{6}-x^{3} y^{3}+x^{6}\right) \\
& \geq(x+y) x y x^{3} y^{3}=(x+y) x^{4} y^{4}
\end{aligned}
$$

The equality sign holds if and only if $x=y$. Using the last inequality, we get

$$
\begin{aligned}
a^{9} b^{9} c^{9} & =\left(a^{9}+b^{9}\right)\left(b^{9}+c^{9}\right)\left(c^{9}+a^{9}\right) \\
& \geq(a+b)(b+c)(c+a) a^{4} b^{4} b^{4} c^{4} c^{4} a^{4}=a^{9} b^{9} c^{9}
\end{aligned}
$$

If $a b c \neq 0$, then the equality sign holds if $a=b=c$. However, substituting into

$$
(a+b)(b+c)(c+a)=a b c
