$$
\frac{p_{n}}{p_{N-1}}=\left(1-b_{N}\right)\left(1-b_{N+1}\right) \ldots\left(1-b_{n}\right) \geqslant 1-b_{N}-\ldots-b_{n}>\frac{1}{2}
$$

These inequalities show that the sequence $p_{n}$ is non-increasing and $p_{n}>p_{N-1} / 2>0$. Therefore, the limit $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} p_{n}$ exists and is not zero.

$$
\begin{aligned}
& \text { 30.35. Let } p_{n}=\prod_{k=1}^{n}\left(1+a_{k}\right) \text { and } P_{n}=\prod_{k=1}^{n}\left(1+\left|a_{k}\right|\right) . \text { Then } \\
& \qquad\left|p_{n}-p_{n-1}\right|=\left|a_{n}\right| \prod_{k=1}^{n-1}\left|1+a_{k}\right| \leqslant\left|a_{n}\right| \prod_{k=1}^{n-1}\left(1+\left|a_{k}\right|\right)=P_{n}-P_{n-1}
\end{aligned}
$$

By the condition, the limit $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} P_{n}$ exists, so the series $\sum\left(P_{n}-P_{n-1}\right)$ converges. But in this case, the series $\sum\left(p_{n}-p_{n-1}\right)$ must also converge, so the limit $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} p_{n}$ exists. We only need to check that this limit is not zero. For this, consider the series $\sum\left|\frac{a_{k}}{1+a_{k}}\right|$. It converges because the series $\sum\left|a_{k}\right|$ converges and the sequence $1+a_{k}$ has a limit of 1. Therefore, the infinite product $\prod\left(1-\frac{a_{k}}{1+a_{k}}\right)$ converges absolutely, so the sequence $q_{n}=\prod_{k=1}^{n}\left(1-\frac{a_{k}}{1+a_{k}}\right)$ has a finite limit. But $q_{n}=p_{n}^{-1}$, so $\lim _{n \rightarrow \infty} p_{n} \neq 0$.

